SA Post Office employees in Durban are accused of forcing grant beneficiaries to pay a fee to be serviced. Or receive preferential treatment by jumping a queue. eNCA's Nkosazana Dambuza fills us in. Courtesy #DStv403 DURBAN - SA Post Office employees in Durban are accused of forcing grant beneficiaries to pay a fee to be serviced. The fee is for the recipient to receive preferential treatment by jumping a queue. Those who refuse to pay bribes are left out in the cold. READ: Post Office reassures social grant recipients The Post Office is defending its employees, saying internal investigations show that members of the public are to blame. They also say there’s no evidence that taxi drivers are involved. * eNCA's Nkosazana Dambuza reports.